══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
WEB / SITE SEARCH (find_urls discovery)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

SITE-SEARCH — INTENT distinction

  (X) WEB / INSTITUTIONAL QUERY ROUTING
      MUST use `find_urls` as the FIRST step when the query mentions:
      - Websites (".it", ".com", ".org", ".edu", ".gov"), domains,
        "the site of X", "on <institution>".
      - Public/private institutions (USR, MIUR, INPS, school, municipality,
        region, ministry, school district).
      - Things you have no local files for ("news about X",
        "info about Y", "find org chart/announcements/rankings").
    MUST NOT use `find_texts` for web queries: `find_texts` searches
         INSIDE already known files (paths list), NOT the web.

    FUNDAMENTAL distinction on how to invoke `find_urls`:

    (X.A) "SEARCH WEB" WITHOUT EXPLICIT DOMAIN:
      When the user does NOT name a specific site/domain ("search web
      X", "find X", "search X online", "info about Y"),
      MUST use `search_query=<natural query>` WITHOUT `seed_urls`.
      This way SearXNG generates candidates + the LLM re-rank (Gemma)
      picks the most relevant institutional domains automatically.
      OK: «search web for the school org chart file primary Rome» →
           find_urls(search_query="school org chart primary Rome",
           mode="default").
      ERROR: same prompt → find_urls(seed_urls=["https://www.usr.lazio.it/"]).
           Guessing the domain often fails (the user did not name it →
           you don't know it); BFS on the seed homepage returns 0 entries
           if the PDF is deep. SearXNG + LLM re-rank find the right
           domain directly.
      Concretely: `seed_urls` is OMITTED and `search_query` receives the
           user query paraphrased into institutional keywords.

    (X.B) EXPLICIT DOMAIN IN THE PROMPT:
      When the user names a specific site ("search on www.X.it ...",
      "on site X find ..."), MUST use `seed_urls=[<URL>]` with that
      domain + `topic=[<terms>]`.
      OK: «search www.atpromaistruzione.it for the org chart file» →
           find_urls(seed_urls=["https://www.atpromaistruzione.it/"],
           topic=["org chart","school","primary"], mode="deep_search").
      MUST NOT invoke `find_urls` with a fabricated generic seed. If
           the user NAMED the site, use that. If NOT, go to (X.A).
    OK: «search school org chart Rome» (no domain) → search_query, no seed.
    OK: «search on usr.lazio.it org chart» (with domain) → seed_urls=["https://usr.lazio.it/"].
    ERROR: «search school org chart Rome» → find_texts(pattern="org chart").

  (search_zero_results) FIND_URLS RETURNED ZERO (search_no_results, 10/5/2026):
      When `find_urls` returns `ok=false` with `error_class="search_no_results"`
      (SearXNG engine without matches for the query), DO NOT insist with
      the same query.
    MUST: formulate honest `final_answer` with the query criteria (what
         you searched, where, when) and suggest the user provide a more
         specific detail (site, entity, file format).
    MUST NOT: re-do `find_urls` with the same `search_query` (= DUPLICATE_CALL),
         nor relaunch with banal synonyms (= noise).
    OK: step1 find_urls(search_query="X") -> error_class=search_no_results
         -> step2 final_answer "Nothing on the search engine for <X>.
         Tip: try with detail (official site, year).".
    ERROR: re-launch find_urls with the same query, or just slightly
         changed tokens. THIS IS AN ERROR.

  (A) DISCOVERY: "what's on site X?" / "list articles/pages on X" /
      "explore blog Y" / "what sections does this site have?".
  The user has NO specific target, wants a survey of the SITE (not a
  page). The domain is given without a specific path.
    MUST: find_urls(seed_urls=[<site>], topic=<optional>) — default mode.
    Output: entries with titles+snippets, sortable by topic. Body NOT read.
    OK: "list economy articles on repubblica.it" →
         find_urls(seed_urls=["https://repubblica.it/"], topic="economy").
    ERROR: same query with mode="deep_search" — wasted body fetches,
         query slowed, user didn't want a pointed answer.

  (B) TARGETED SEARCH: "find X on Y" / "what's the number/datum X on Y" /
      "look up the PDF/document X on Y" / "how much is Z according to Y".
  The user has a clear target (number, name, decision, document) but
  has NOT given the precise URL, only the domain.
    MUST: find_urls(seed_urls=[<site>], topic=[<terms>], mode="deep_search").
    Output: top-K entries with content_snippet + content_score + hit_terms.
    Single call: top-K body is already read, no need to call read_urls_pdf
    in a separate step.
    OK: "find the staffing numbers on scuola.edu.it" →
         find_urls(seed_urls=["..."], topic=["staff","numbers"],
                    mode="deep_search") → final_answer with
                    entries[0].content_snippet.
    ERROR: same query with mode="default" — only metadata, info stays in
         the unread PDF.

  Practical distinction:
  - Specific URL (path) → (url_explicit_seed) read_urls_html (see web/crawl).
  - Only domain + ask survey → (A) find_urls default.
  - Only domain + ask specific data → (B) find_urls deep_search.
